Welcome! Want to try a nutritious, delicious smoothie?
No smoothie?\nWell, if you change your mind...
Sorry, the smoothie machine's down for maintenance.\nSwing by next time!
We're working on a new crepe menu with local loquats!\nFancy fruit crepes sound like a hit, right?
I heard there was some kind of commotion\nat the old shipyard the other night. Kinda creepy, huh?
Sure, there are food trucks by the station...\nBut here, you can enjoy your food with an ocean view!
Even the former Northbright kids have started coming by!\nThat merger's been great for business!
We've got limited-edition Football Frontier Crepes on sale!\nIt's a special item inspired by the tournament!
Weekly Eleven did a feature on football-themed food!\nI hope our shop makes it in there someday!
Oh! I saw your match against Royal Academy!\nOur Football Frontier Crepes were flying off the shelves!
He used to go to\nBrainwashing Jr. High...
Manager <LST:SHIMOZURU> from Northbright? He's from Kanto, right?\nI heard he even played in the Football Frontier back in the day!
I end up rewatching\nthe whole match!
Football Frontier season is wild!\nThere are so many youth football events, my schedule's jam-packed!
Raimon's just built different this year.\nWith <FUL:HARU> on the team, they're next-level.
So Perfect Football Northbright is basically breaking up.\nEven the powerhouse schools can't escape reality, huh...
Wait—are you...?! No, no, as a fan,\nI won't dig into your private life!
I saw <FUL:HARU> in real life the other day!\nHe looked like he was just strolling about,\nbut... is his injury okay?
Raimon's still winning without him,\nbut when <FST:HARU> was on the pitch,\nthey felt straight-up unbeatable.
Where is he now,\nand what's he doing?
Not even a single\npost on socials...
Where is <FST:HARU>, seriously? No word on his injury,\nand the finals are just around the corner...
Maybe I'll grab one\nto take home.
I wanna catch the\nmatch broadcast too.
You can really taste the\nlove that went into this...
<FST:SORAMIYA> lost in the Spring Cup, but wow, he looked so cool!\nI'm gonna be the heart of my team someday too!
I heard <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High started a football club!\nWonder what kind of team they'll become...
Can you believe <FUL:HARU> was at the Civic Stadium?\nHe got subbed out midway, but those shots—whoa!
They say <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> is pulling off a real underdog story!\nI wanna do that too someday...
I dream of joining Royal Academy's football club!\nBut I'd have to move to Tokyo first...
That armored vehicle Royal Academy uses?\nSo cool! I wanna ride in it someday...
Whoa, you beat Alice in Footballand?!\nAre you, like, a genius or something?!
This view... reminds me of a brilliant thriller I saw recently.\n<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> gets used as a filming location quite a lot,\nyou know.
I'm seeing a film soon that was directed by a footballer.\nPeople say it really captures the feeling of a live match.
They used old-fashioned marble soap in a scene I watched recently.\nSeeing something so familiar on screen made me smile.
I visited the flower fields at Cupid's Carnival—simply breathtaking.\nThey'd make a perfect backdrop for something fantastical.
I hear there's a campaign for youth football fans.\nHah, live matches screened right in the theater.
Watching live football at the theater is quite the experience.\nThe energy when everyone cheers... I go quite often.
I can't take my eyes off <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>'s dramatic rise.\nLooks like I've become a youth football fan myself.
I wanna go to\nRai Rai Noodles!
Travel is expensive\nthis time of year.
Ah, hang on. I'm trying out some ideas with this monument right now!
I want to show people how great <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> is,\nso I'm trying to snap some pics for social media.
Have you been to Champon Bluespring?\nIt's got the best champon in all of <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>!
Aren't they a bad\ninfluence on the kids?
Have you heard of Breeze? They're a trio of middle-aged guys\nwho perform as cheerleader idols down at Cove Beach!
They're from our\nlocal school, after all!
I hope more people find\nout about our town!
I pray to the <FUL:UMIBOZU> every day\nfor <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> to keep winning!
Have you seen <FUL:MAN-TAICHO>'s <FUL:MANMANTV>?\nIt's got a bunch of videos about <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High!
<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High got a flight hub for Odaiba, right?\nIt's crazy to see our town connected to Football Frontier like that.
A seventh grader, and\nalready a manager, huh?
I even saw it in\nEleven magazine.
Oh hey, <FUL:UNMEI>!\nWe're counting on you to carry <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> 's name with pride!
I've been going to the gym, but it's just not cutting it.\nHonestly thinking of trying Aquacore Fitness.\nI hear their training's tough.
I heard there are more\nsports clubs now.
These days, it's rare for a school not to have a football club.\nI wonder what club the football fans joined before.
Word is, it's all\nfor the football club...
<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High's putting a lot of money into sports clubs.\nBeing private probably helps too.
I've been feeling great ever since I joined Aquacore Fitness.\nThe instructors there really know their stuff.
That's just how it goes\nout here.
The new shoes I wanted still haven't arrived in <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>...\nI'm so jealous of city folks who can buy them on release day.
No one knows how old\nshe actually is!
The instructor at the fitness class I go to is so beautiful.\nShe looks way too young to have a son in junior high.
Ms. <FST:OTOHINA>'s son was incredible in the last match.\nWe've gotta cheer him on for the finals!
We've got to keep this view well maintained to show our hospitality.\nIt's the first thing people see when they get off the boat, after all.
A lot of people pass through here, so the trash bins fill up quickly.\nBut it's good to see that people still use them instead of littering.
I'm thinking of toilet-training the stray cats around the port.\nCleaning up after their messes is such a hassle.
Oh, some <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> students helped with trash cleanup.\nKids from good schools really stand out.
My son's volunteering at the grand finals. He's neat like me,\nso he's probably handling the garden cleanup.
Whew... As the hot season comes,\nworking outside is only going to get harder.
The weather's really warmed up lately!\nIce cream in spring has its own special charm.
That rose shape is made with just a single spatula.\nIt's like magic, isn't it?
This ice cream was once sold by bell-ringing vendors.\nToday, we call it "Chilling Ice Cream"\nbecause it's as cool as it sounds.
The icy crunch of Chilling Ice Cream pairs perfectly\nwith a crispy cone. It's the ultimate combo!
The ice cream still tastes just like the original recipe.\nBut <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> has changed a lot over the years.
This stand is super eco-friendly! No electricity used whatsoever.\nWe keep the ice cream cold with ice and salt.
How about a sweet treat to brighten today's memories?\nCare for a Chilling Ice Cream?
I could use a bit\nof cooling off.
Hey, you look like a sharp one! Why not try a trial lesson?\nWe've got advanced classes for kids at <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> and West Manor!
A lot of kids apply to <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> because of parental pressure.\nIt's only natural. They want the best place for their kids to grow.
Northbright's the big name when it comes to public schools.\nThey've got a top-tier football program, after all.
Can you believe <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> and Northbright are merging?\nParents must be stressing out over things like tuition and uniforms.
I was working hard to save up for the new CHAMP-ON cap...\nbut it sold out before I could afford it.
<FUL:HARU> played at Civic Stadium...\nIf it hadn't been a workday, I'd have run straight there!
Nothing beats Rai Rai Noodles after work.\nThink I'll go with three slices of meat today.
Whoa—hey, you... Do people ever say you look like <FUL:HARU>?\nBet you get that a lot.
I really wanna take the day off for the grand finals...\nbut with this month's schedule? No chance.
Our boss gets way too into Football Frontier.\nI asked why, and turns out he's a <MNT:NAGUMOHARA> alum.
I'm planning to watch the finals with the crew from work.\nLet's go, Kyushu reps!
I've been glued to international football matches, and now I really\nwant to watch one live! But man, it's gotta be crazy expensive...
I started going to language classes to keep up with\ninternational football news, but wow, foreign languages are tough.
Those young players who head abroad right after graduation?\nI respect how they squeeze in language study between all their training.
A tourist asked me about the <FUL:UMIBOZU> statue,\nbut all I could say was, "Sorry, no idea!"
Eastwind International was strong—especially <FUL:KAI>!\nThe way he plays? I'm a fan now.
I was talking to some overseas fans about <FUL:ENDO>.\nEveryone got fired up! The guy's a legend across borders.
I'm heading overseas with some friends to catch a pro league match!\nFirst time traveling abroad, so yeah... kinda nervous.
New things have always come in through the port, then and now.\nWe've got to keep that spirit of trying new things alive.
A ship has to reach its destination. So if you have a dream,\nmake sure you see it through, no matter what form it takes.
You can't talk about Nagasaki's history without mentioning the port.\nThat's exactly why I want young folks to treasure this place.
My ancestors worked as interpreters in overseas trade.\nAn important role back when the port first opened to the world.
The best sailors face rough seas together.\nI hope you find companions who'll stick with you\nthrough thick and thin.
Are you taking good care of the <FUL:UMIBOZU> statues around town?\nIt's up to your generation to keep those traditions alive.
<MNT:NAGUMOHARA> Junior High's been popping up\nall over the media lately. Hopefully that means more tourists\nwill start visiting the port too.
Make sure to take\nyour hooks with you.
Please don't throw\ntrash into the sea.
Don't leave your bike\nblocking the walkway!
Keep an eye on your\nkids near the water.
I really don't want\nto get seasick.
I should take some\nmotion sickness meds.
Just hope the sea\nwon't be rough today.
Whoops, thought that\nwas the No. 9 West Bus.
Wonder if they sell\nthose on board.
A cruise around the\nworld sounds amazing.
I'd love to get on\nthat ship...
Might as well kill\nsome time while I wait.
He's kinda hard\nto get close to.
Yeah, from the drama\nclub, he's a bit...
He comes from a family\nof classic performers.
Feels like he's from a\ntotally different world.
Wish I could go back\nto that classroom.
The football club's\nlooking for new blood.
It's not like you\nhave to say yes, right?
I made extras\nfor you guys too!
Let's all use them—\ncheer squad time!
Rumor says it happened in class...
And honestly, I can see her doing it.
Yeah, she doesn't hold back,\neven on adults...
Turns out they're chill\nonce you talk to 'em.
Just passed a seriously rough-looking trio. Judging by their eyes,\nI'd say they're definitely from the criminal side of things.
They say <FUL:HOSHI> from the Modern Music Club\nmade a teacher cry with her sharp tongue.\nAnd honestly? With her, it sounds totally believable...
A merger without telling the students first? Doesn't feel right—\nbut I guess that's what they call "adult decisions."
Watching that match against Eastwind International, I realized...\nmerging with Northbright might've actually benefited <MNT:NAGUMOHARA>.
Saw a rumor on the school app that the principal's an idol fan.\nI'm more curious about where that started.
Getting interviewed by a reporter from Eleven, huh?\nEven you must've felt the pressure a little, right?
So this is the famous\nBeppu Springs, huh...
They say, "Soak once and you'll be a beauty for life!"\nThink even an old bat like me stands a chance? Hee hee...
You ever heard of Twinford Village?\nThey say folks there greet you with the warmest smiles.
Life in the sticks\nain't always kind...
Seems like schools in Kyushu are merging left and right these days.\nEven back in Fukuoka, a couple of junior highs got bundled together.
I hear they had a big festival down in Okinawa.\nWhole village pitched in—they must've had a grand ol' time.
Hee hee hee... They say that gang, the Back Alley Kickers,\ncleaned up their act thanks to football. Imagine that!
Over in Twinford Village, there's this place called GreenGrin Park.\nHeard the mayor runs the place himself!
